The '''black-browed triller''' ('''''Lalage atrovirens''''') is a species of [[bird]] in the family [[Campephagidae]]. It is found in northern [[New Guinea]]. Its natural [[habitat]]s are subtropical or tropical moist lowland [[forest]]s and subtropical or tropical mangrove forests. The [[Biak triller]] (''L. leucoptera'') was formerly considered a subspecies.<ref name=":1">{{Cite web|title=Species Updates – IOC World Bird List|url=https://www.worldbirdnames.org/new/updates/species-updates/|access-date=4 June 2021|language=en-US}}</ref> It is very vocal, and often travels in flocks with other species.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Diamond |first=Jared |last2=Bishop |first2=K. David |last3=Sneider |first3=Richard |date=10 October 2019 |title=An avifaunal double suture zone at the Bird's Neck Isthmus of New Guinea |journal=The Wilson Journal of Ornithology |volume=131 |issue=3 |page=435 |doi=10.1676/18-167 |issn=1559-4491}}</ref> Like many bird species of New Guinea, very little is known about it.

